<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the Law Society of England and Wales (LAI 0049)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is the Law Society’s response to the J</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oint Committee on Human Rights (JCHR) call for evidence on the access to justice implications of the civil legal aid proposals in the government's  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  consultation paper. The JCHR has specifically requested evidence in relation to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">following proposals:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid claimants, so as to limit legal aid to those with a “strong connection” with the UK </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposed restriction on the scope of legal aid available to prisoners </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The propo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court grants permission for the application to proceed </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposal that legal aid should be re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">moved for al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l cases assessed as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">having “borderline” prospects of success. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overarching concerns about the proposals</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Law Society has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">two primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">concerns with the proposals that are only partly mitigated by the amendments announced in the Government Response on 5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">September. These include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">First, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here is a genuine risk that all four proposals will lead to the erosion of access to justice, particularly in relation to cases against public bodies.  As a consequence, public bodies may increasingly be able to act with i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mpunity as the ability of citizens to challenge them is reduced.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 11pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Second, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he proposals, which risk depriving the poorest and most vulnerable citizens of a legal remedy, are potentially detrimental to the concept of equality before the law and the ability o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f all citizens to have equal access to justice.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Legitimacy of  the government's objectives</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are two fundamental stated objec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tives behind the proposals in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. These are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To further reduce the cost of legal aid; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To restore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public confidence in legal aid.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Society questioned these objectives on the basis that overall, even before the £3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">0 million pound per </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">annum cuts brought in on 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> April 2013 under the Legal Aid Sentencing and P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unishment of Offenders Act  (LASPO), legal aid costs were actually falling. We also pointed out that the government failed to provide any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">compelling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evidence that public confidence in legal aid has been undermined. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he savings relating to these proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are minimal. According to the MOJ's impact assessments the prison law scope cuts will save £4 million per annum, the judicial review funding cut will save £1 million and the abolition of the 'borderline' merits test will save £1million. The savings result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing from the residence test are un-quantified and there is no evidence to suggest that legal aid provided to those who would not meet the residence test is a significant drain on public funds. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore  the government has been unable to point to any e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vidence that these measures are required to sustain public confidence in the legal aid system and there is no assessment of the knock-on costs, both social and financial, of the reduction in access to justice the proposals will entail.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For these reasons o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur view is that these proposals will not meet the government's objectives to any significant degree.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prison Law scope cuts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposal is that the scope of legal aid for prison law will be limited to:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cases involving the determination of a criminal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charge for the purposes of Article 6 ECHR (right to a fair trial);</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cases engaging Article 5.4 ECHR (right to have ongoing detention reviewed); and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The most serious disciplinary matters that meet the 'Tarrant Criteria'.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This means that all treatment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cases as well as sentencing and disciplinary matters that do not meet the above criteria, will no longer be eligible for legal aid. The MOJ estimate this proposal will lead to 11,000 fewer funded cases per year producing a costs saving of £4 million.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Society’s view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is that imprisonment should not deprive prisoners of protection of their basic human rights.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have particular concerns about the impact  on  prisoners with mental health and learning disabilities who cannot reasonably be expected to negot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iate the internal complaints procedures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">without assistance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are sceptical of the MOJ assurance that 'reasonable adjustments' will be made to internal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> complaints procedures to make them accessible to prisoners with mental health problems or learning disabilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Without the ever present risk of legal intervention a strong incentive to maintain an effective system is removed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The cuts will disproportio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nately impact on black and ethnic minority males who are disproportionately represented in the prison population.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A residence test that will make 12 months lawful residence in the UK a requirement for eligibility for civil legal aid.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Proposals which ris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k reducing access to justice should only be made with reference to compelling evidence. In our view, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he MOJ has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> produced evidence of the scale of civil legal aid use by those with little connection to the UK and they have no estimate as to whether any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> costs savings will be generated by the proposal.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should be noted that the proposed test </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would effectively deprive non-UK nationals abroad of the ability to seek redress for injustice by the UK Government. Examples include the Gurkha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ex-servicemen who sought a right to reside in the UK and victims of miscon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duct by British troops in Iraq.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It will affect both UK  and EU nationals who do not meet the 12 months residence rule.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he test</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is administratively unworkable:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it wil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l have to be applied by solicitors who will be forced into a q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uasi immigration officer role. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to avoid discrimination, all civil clients including UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nationals will have to be subject to the residence test and the majority will be eligible. However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the administrative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scale of the task is immense. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012-13 alone there were 590,410 civil Legal Help funded acts of assistance and 139,082 civil legal aid certificates granted. So in this one year alone, each of these 729,483 acts of assistance would have needed to be preceded by a residence test admini</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stered by solicitors before any funding was available. The LASPO scope cuts will reduce the overall numbers going forward, but the number will still be significant. Many clients will not have the documents required to prove their nationality or the 12 mont</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hs residence requirement. This creates a further barrier to obtaining legal aid particularly for those in the most difficult circumstances who are least likely to be able to produce the necessary documents. Examples include homeless people , people with me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntal health and community care needs, and victims of forced marriage. This test will be a major deterrent to civil legal aid providers, especially in family law which, post LASPO, represents the main bulk of civil legal aid cases. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, we believe tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t the test may be contrary to established law for the following reasons:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disproportionate adverse effect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of a residence test </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on non UK nationals may amount to unlawful discrimination. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is likely to be unlawful under s29 of the Equali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which prohibits discrimination in the provision of services including those provided by public authorities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> If </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the residence test amounts to unlawful discrimination on the ground of nationality, there is no statutory defence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the Equality Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It may be discriminatory under Article 14 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(prohibition of discrimination) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">combined with Article 6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(right to a fair trial) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Article 14 requires that there should be no unjustified </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">diff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erence of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">treatment between people who are similarly placed in relation to rights guaranteed by the Convention. As </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">legal aid is only available for matters of English law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for proceedings before domestic courts it is difficult to see how residence status can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">legal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">basis for distinguishing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> between people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the purpose of legal aid eligibility.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Article 1 requires states to secure Convention rights to 'everyone within their jurisdiction'.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A change of this nature interferes with the common law rights </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of access to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">courts and non discrimination.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> According to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the now well-established common </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">law principle of legality, the general words of the power to make regulations in LASPO are not apt to allow such a fundamental interference with constitutional ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ghts, which can only be effected by primary legislation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It may also fall foul of EU prohibitions of discrimination on grounds of nationality and EU law provisions such as Article 47 of the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights which provides that legal aid sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all be made available to those who lack sufficient resources to ensure effective access to justice in relation to the implementation of EU law.  It may also be contrary, depending on the circumstances of the case, to legal aid provisions under Council Dire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ctive 2002/8/EC which provides that persons involved in cross border disputes are entitled to appropriate legal aid to obtain effective access to justice. Article 4 of the Directive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">states that legal aid must be made available without discrimination to EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">citizens and third country nationals residing lawfully in a member state. The 12 month qualification rule is incompatible with this provision.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The government's response to consultation regarding the residence test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We acknowledge that the government has listened to some of the concerns raised by respondents to the consultation regarding the residence test.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Several useful amendments have been made that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exempt detention cases, victims of trafficking and  domestic viol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ence, protection of children cases and Special Immigration Appeals Commission cases from having to satisfy the residence test. We also welcome the clarification that those submitting fresh asylum claims will be treated in the same way as initial asylum cla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imants and that those granted refugee status will be entitled to legal aid (on other issues) after 12 months from the date of their claim rather than 12 months from the date their claim was determined. The concession to exempt babies from the 12 months res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">idence requirement is also to be welcomed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although these concessions are a step in the right direction they do not negate our concerns that the test remains fundamentally discriminatory and potentially unlawful under English and EU law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e would like to see clarification of the government's argument at paragraph 115 of their response that exceptional funding will be available under s10 of LASPO if a person </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">excluded from legal aid by the residence test where a Human Rights Act matter is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in issue. Our understanding is that s10 funding is only available where the legal issue is out of scope rather than because the applicant is ineligible for legal aid. If the government is to bring those applicants within the scope of s10, we would need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">see the draft amendment to LASPO Schedule 1 before we can comment further.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have serious concerns about the operation of the exceptional funding scheme as the exceptional funding test is itself a significant barrier to obtaining legal aid. Prior to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">implementation of LASPO, the MOJ estimated there would be approximately 6000 exceptional funding applications a year. After approximately 6 months since the implementation of LASPO only 566 exceptional funding applications have been considered by the LAA a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd of those, a mere 11 applications have been granted. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pplicants for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exceptional funding cannot get Legal H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elp to assist them with framing their applications in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">convention or EU rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The operation of exceptional funding as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">'safety net' for those with important cases that would not otherwise qualify for legal aid must be fully reviewed before the remit of exceptional funding is extended.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Judicial review funding cuts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposal is that lawyers will only be entitled to leg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al aid costs for judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(JR) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">applications where permission is granted. Legally aided clients will still be entitled to pre-permission disbursements and will retain protection from costs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The MOJ argue that the difference between the number of JR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">legal aid certificates issued and the smaller number of permission applications granted is indicative of unmeritorious applications being pursued. They do not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in our view, sufficiently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> acknowledge that many JR cases settle in the applicant's favour before</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> permission is granted.  In these cases solicitors will not be able to recover their costs even though they have achieved a positive outcome for their client. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This creates a perverse incentive not to settle before permission and could actually increase r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">her than decrease overall costs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In some cases l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">awyers may not be prepared to accept the risk of taking on JR cases, thus reducing access to justice to challenge unreasonable decisions of the state.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To the extent that the proposal has the effect of lim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iting access to legal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">representation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it may engage Article 6 of the EHCR and Article 47 of the EU Charter on Fundamental Rights. In particular, it provides extra protection for public authorities against claims and the lack of proper legal aid funding means there is no effective access to ju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stice in these cases. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposal risks a perception that the government's objective is to undermine the ability of citizens to challenge the government and other public bodies. It follows on from recently implemented changes that reduced the time limit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s for bringing certain JRs and significantly increased JR court fees.  Additionally the government has recently published a further consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: Proposals for Further Reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which has the stated aim of reducing the number of JR applicatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns. We refer to this is more detail below</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The effects of this proposal should also be considered in conjunction with the proposal (below) to abolish the 'borderline' merits criterion which in itself is likely to have a limiting effect on legal aid avail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ability for JR, where the outcome of an application can be notoriously difficult to predict. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The MOJ estimate this proposal will save just £1million per annum.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The government's response to consultation regarding JR funding and further consultation on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> JR</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In its response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consultation the government accepted respondents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">'</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concerns that the initial JR funding proposal would adversely affect meritorious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">applications that are settled before permission is granted. It is now proposed that the Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (LAA) should have a discretion to fund certain cases that conclude before permission is granted. The details of this proposal together with a raft of other proposals for the reform of JR are set out in the new consultation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: Proposa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ls for Further Reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The criteria that the LAA would use to determine whether an application is funded when a case is concluded before the permission stage are listed as: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reason for the provider not obtaining a costs agreement (whether in full or in part) as part of any settlement, not seeking a costs order, or the court not awarding a costs order (whether in full or part). This will include consideration of the conduct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the provider under the pre-action protocol and in the proceedings; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The extent to which the client obtained the remedy, redress or benefit they had been seeking in the proceedings; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reason why the client in fact obtained any remedy, redress or be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nefit they had been seeking in the proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The likelihood, considered at the point the settlement is made (or the case is otherwise concluded), of permission having been granted if the application had been considered, whether from a specific ind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ication in the proceedings by the Court or based on the strength of the claim at that point.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As this consultation has only recently  been issued we have not yet had the opportunity to fully consider this proposal. However our initial thinking is that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> criteria are too vague and susceptible to subjective interpretation. The LAA is considered by many providers to be highly risk averse when it comes to payment of costs. It is important, if the discretionary funding is to operate as the Ministry intends, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat the criteria are drafted in such a way that many of the important cases that settle with substantive benefit prior to permission continue to receive funding. We will look to work closely with the LAA to provide the insight of frontline practitioners in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the drafting and development of these criteria to ensure that they are fit for purpose.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are not convinced that, at present, this proposal will encourage providers who are reluctant to put their costs at risk in JR applications to take on these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">importan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Removing the ‘borderline’ merits test criterion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This means that 'borderline' cases, i.e. those where it is not possible to say that there is a 50% or greater chance of success will n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o longer qualify for legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The MOJ accept that 'borderline' cases are often 'high priority' cases involving holding the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tate to account, public interest cases or housing cases. These are, almost by definition, cases where prospects of success are difficult to assess because they tu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rn on very specific facts or seek to clarify the law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The MOJ claim that the ability to appeal refusals of legal aid provides a sufficient safeguard, but this just places an additional barrier to public funding and will result in increased costs and delay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s for cases that are often urgent. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The MOJ estimate this proposal will affect around 100 cases per year and save just £1million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per annum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Given the acknowledged high priority of some of these cases the proposal seems disproportionately damaging given th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scale of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> likely savings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A number of important test cases have initially been assessed as 'borderline' and we do not accept that the minimal cost saving can justify the loss of access to justice and possibilities for clarifying the law that will res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ult form the 'borderline' criterion being abolished.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Equalities Issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The MOJ's Equalities Impact Assessment does accept that some of these proposals have a disproportionate impact on protected groups, but they argue that the measures are proportionate to achieving the 'legitimate aims' of the proposals.  In the 'Legitimacy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the government's objectives' section above we question whether the case for the government’s primary aims, (costs savings and public confidence) has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been compellingly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> made out.  If, as we have suggested, it has not, there must be an argument that the im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pacts on protected groups cannot be justified in terms of the Equalit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Act.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Page </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>